Raw dev notes -- Building a Persistent Browser Wrapper for a Web App API (late March 2026)

This week I refactored a REST API wrapper I built around a web application that doesn't
have an official API. The old approach extracted auth tokens and replayed them with an HTTP
client -- fragile, broke every few hours. The new idea: keep a persistent headless browser
running and execute all API calls INSIDE it via page.evaluate(fetch). The browser IS the session.

Key commits/milestones:
- Replaced custom HTTP client with a community SDK
- Built persistent browser profile for automatic session reuse
- Moved to browser-as-runtime: all calls via Playwright page.evaluate(fetch)
- Built a 24h endurance test with simulated user interactions across multiple sessions
- Handled various login flow edge cases (account chooser, changing selectors)
- Fixed corrupt browser cache on startup

Struggles:
- Auth tokens expire unpredictably. Tried refreshing on various intervals with jitter
- Auto-retry with rebuilt client was tricky -- had to distinguish auth vs transient errors
- Periodic page refresh killed the session instead of keeping it alive (counterintuitive!)
- Login UI selectors kept changing across updates

Reflection: The key insight is that fighting a web app's auth system is futile. Instead of
extracting tokens, just let the browser handle everything natively. It's like the difference
between reverse-engineering an API and just using the website. Sometimes the 'lazy' approach
is the smart one.

Next: Better error recovery, source pipeline, concurrent user support.
